45. DSA Parameter Tampering

Exploiting weak generator g in DSA

Step 1
Given:
DSA parameters (p, q, g)

    Modify:
    g = 0

Step 2
> DSA Signature Components
    r = (g^k mod p) mod q
    s = (k⁻¹ * (H(msg) + x·r)) mod q

Step 3
> Substitute g = 0

    r = (0^k mod p) mod q
    r = 0
    
    s = (k⁻¹ * (H(msg) + x·0)) mod q
    s = (k⁻¹ * H(msg)) mod q

- r is always 0
- s depends only on message hash

Step 4
> Verification Behavior

Verification checks:
v = ((g^(H(msg)/s) * y^(r/s)) mod p) mod q

Since r = 0:
    y^(r/s) = y^0 = 1
    
    g = 0 → g^(...) = 0
    v = 0

Result:
    v == r → valid

- Any signature with r = 0 passes verification
- Any message is accepted

Step 5
> Using g = p + 1
Property:
    g mod p = 1

Step 6
> Effect on r
    r = ((p+1)^k mod p) mod q
    r = (1^k mod p) mod q
    r = 1 mod q

Step 7
> Construct Magic Signature

For any value z:

    r = (y^z \bmod p) \bmod q
    s = r \cdot z^{-1} \bmod q

- z = arbitrary chosen value
- no need for private key x
- no need for real k

Step 8
> Result
Generated (r, s) is valid for:
  - any message
  - any public key y

Examples:
"Hello, world"
"Goodbye, world"

Both verify successfully with same (r, s)



CODE (Java)

import java.math.BigInteger;

public class DSAParameterTampering {
public static void main(String[] args) {  

    BigInteger p = new BigInteger("800000000000000089e1855218a0e7dac38136ffafa72eda7...", 16);  
    BigInteger q = new BigInteger("f4f47f05794b256174bba6e9b396a7707e563c5b", 16);  

    BigInteger y = new BigInteger("2d026f4bf30195ede3a088da85e398ef869611d0f68f07...", 16);  

    BigInteger g = p.add(BigInteger.ONE);  

    BigInteger z = new BigInteger("12345");  

    BigInteger r = y.modPow(z, p).mod(q);  
    BigInteger s = r.multiply(z.modInverse(q)).mod(q);  

    System.out.println("Magic Signature:");  
    System.out.println("r = " + r);  
    System.out.println("s = " + s);  
}  
}

Notes:

> g = 0
  - forces r = 0
  - signature becomes universally valid
> g = p + 1
  - behaves as 1 mod p
  - allows construction of fake signatures

> z
  - arbitrary value chosen by attacker
> modInverse(q)
  - used to compute division mod q


> Manipulating generator g breaks DSA security
g = 0 → all signatures valid
g = p + 1 → forge signatures without private key
> Proper parameter validation is required
